$\begin{align}
&x = r\cos(\theta) \\ \\
&y = r\sin(\theta) \\ \\
&f(x, y) = e^{x^2 + y^2} = e^{r^2(\cos^2(\theta) + \sin^2(\theta))} = e^{r^2}
\end{align}$

To find what we want to integrate, we first need to find what $x$ and $y$ become in polar coordinates, then substitute that into $f$.

$\begin{align}
&x = r\cos(\theta) \\ \\
&y = r\sin(\theta) \\ \\
&f(x, y) = \dfrac{1}{x} + \dfrac{2}{y} = \dfrac{1}{r\cos(\theta)} + \dfrac{2}{r\sin(\theta)}
\end{align}$
